00:09:33.850 --> 00:09:34.340
All right.

00:09:34.340 --> 00:09:35.650
ERIC SCHMIDT: And Android
is five times

00:09:35.650 --> 00:09:36.650
larger than the iPhone.

00:09:36.650 --> 00:09:37.160
STEPHEN COLBERT: I know.

00:09:37.160 --> 00:09:39.670
I know.

00:09:39.670 --> 00:09:40.540
ERIC SCHMIDT: And Google
Play runs on that.

00:09:40.540 --> 00:09:41.350
STEPHEN COLBERT: No, I
read that someplace.

00:09:41.350 --> 00:09:43.370
ERIC SCHMIDT: So people will
actually be reading your book

00:09:43.370 --> 00:09:45.910
on the most popular
operating system.

00:09:45.910 --> 00:09:48.310
STEPHEN COLBERT: Then it's going
to make my book better.

00:09:48.310 --> 00:09:49.220
ERIC SCHMIDT: Absolutely.

00:09:49.220 --> 00:09:49.710
STEPHEN COLBERT: OK.

00:09:49.710 --> 00:09:51.000
ERIC SCHMIDT: Which is
why we support it.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:51.380
STEPHEN COLBERT: Great.

00:09:51.380 --> 00:09:52.210
ERIC SCHMIDT: Good.

00:09:52.210 --> 00:09:53.910
Let's try--

00:09:53.910 --> 00:09:55.420
STEPHEN COLBERT: I have
a Google tablet.

00:09:55.420 --> 00:09:56.270
I have a Google tablet.

00:09:56.270 --> 00:09:57.980
I have that little
Google tablet.

00:09:57.980 --> 00:10:00.450
It's got that slightly pebbled
finish and everything.

00:10:00.450 --> 00:10:01.250
ERIC SCHMIDT: It's phenomenally
successful.

00:10:01.250 --> 00:10:02.800
STEPHEN COLBERT: Can I
make a suggestion?

00:10:02.800 --> 00:10:03.180
ERIC SCHMIDT: Yes.

00:10:03.180 --> 00:10:05.750
STEPHEN COLBERT: Can I add an
external volume thing on it?

00:10:05.750 --> 00:10:06.120
ERIC SCHMIDT: Yeah.

00:10:06.120 --> 00:10:07.190
STEPHEN COLBERT: Because you
actually got to go into a

00:10:07.190 --> 00:10:08.510
screen to do the volume.

00:10:08.510 --> 00:10:09.270
An external--

00:10:09.270 --> 00:10:10.520
ERIC SCHMIDT: That
would cost extra.

00:10:12.640 --> 00:10:15.740
STEPHEN COLBERT: I'm
made of money.

00:10:15.740 --> 00:10:17.160
ERIC SCHMIDT: OK.

00:10:17.160 --> 00:10:18.430
STEPHEN COLBERT: After
this thing--

00:10:18.430 --> 00:10:22.940
ERIC SCHMIDT: I want to explore
the precedents that

00:10:22.940 --> 00:10:26.390
brought you to this view of
American exceptionalism.

00:10:26.390 --> 00:10:32.140
And I want to understand why
"A Man for All Seasons" is

00:10:32.140 --> 00:10:33.870
your most favorite book.

00:10:33.870 --> 00:10:36.570
STEPHEN COLBERT: Well,
it's a play.

00:10:36.570 --> 00:10:39.020
But the book form of it is
actually one of my favorite

00:10:39.020 --> 00:10:39.540
things to read.

00:10:39.540 --> 00:10:42.160
The introduction to "A Man For
All Seasons," which is by

00:10:42.160 --> 00:10:43.960
Robert Bolt-- and if you've
never seen it, it's the story

00:10:43.960 --> 00:10:45.610
of Sir Thomas More,
or Saint Thomas

00:10:45.610 --> 00:10:46.900
More if you're a Catholic.

00:10:46.900 --> 00:10:49.040
And I'm a Catholic.

00:10:49.040 --> 00:10:52.150
And it's the story of the man
who was a friend of the king,

00:10:52.150 --> 00:10:52.810
King Henry VIII.

00:10:52.810 --> 00:10:54.310
And he was made chancellor
of England.

00:10:54.310 --> 00:10:56.730
And Henry wanted to get rid
of his wife, be done with

00:10:56.730 --> 00:10:59.070
Catherine and get Anne
Boleyn in there.

00:10:59.070 --> 00:11:02.270
And Thomas More wouldn't put
his hand on a little black

00:11:02.270 --> 00:11:04.970
book, raise his hand and say,
I agree with the king.

00:11:04.970 --> 00:11:06.650
He just stayed silent, wouldn't
say anything.

00:11:06.650 --> 00:11:08.040
And Henry chopped
his head off.

00:11:08.040 --> 00:11:10.200
ERIC SCHMIDT: We saw this
in "The Tudors."

00:11:10.200 --> 00:11:10.570
STEPHEN COLBERT: Yeah.

00:11:10.570 --> 00:11:13.030
It's a little different
in the play.

00:11:13.030 --> 00:11:19.400
But less of this in the
Robert Bolt version.

00:11:19.400 --> 00:11:26.360
I really like it, because it's
the story about essentially,

00:11:26.360 --> 00:11:30.240
is there any part of you, as
More says, is there any part

00:11:30.240 --> 00:11:33.370
of you that is not
your appetites?

00:11:33.370 --> 00:11:35.560
Is there any part of you
that is not your fears

00:11:35.560 --> 00:11:36.730
and not your desires?

00:11:36.730 --> 00:11:38.152
In other words, is there
any part of you that

00:11:38.152 --> 00:11:39.270
doesn't want or reject?

00:11:39.270 --> 00:11:41.670
Is there any part of you that is
just you and from which you

00:11:41.670 --> 00:11:42.900
cannot retreat?

00:11:42.900 --> 00:11:43.970
And

00:11:43.970 --> 00:11:47.110
When I first started doing the
show, I asked, especially the

00:11:47.110 --> 00:11:50.670
people who were at the head of
my show, for instance, Allison

00:11:50.670 --> 00:11:52.220
Silverman, who was my
original executive.

00:11:52.220 --> 00:11:55.150
No, she was my first
head writer.

00:11:55.150 --> 00:11:57.020
I said, I'd love you
to read this essay.

00:11:57.020 --> 00:11:59.240
Because certainly during the
Bush administration, there was

00:11:59.240 --> 00:12:04.080
no criticism of President Bush
when he first started.

00:12:04.080 --> 00:12:05.850
We tried to fix that.

00:12:05.850 --> 00:12:07.490
ERIC SCHMIDT: Yes, I'm going
to come back to that.

00:12:07.490 --> 00:12:07.890
STEPHEN COLBERT: What?

00:12:07.890 --> 00:12:08.400
ERIC SCHMIDT: I'm going
to come back.

00:12:08.400 --> 00:12:09.790
STEPHEN COLBERT: OK.

00:12:09.790 --> 00:12:14.020
And there were so many people
who were afraid to be critical

00:12:14.020 --> 00:12:15.880
of the government at all because
you could be called

00:12:15.880 --> 00:12:17.000
anti-American.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:21.030
And I love the play, because in
this example, he loves the

00:12:21.030 --> 00:12:24.850
king but can't agree with him,
in the same way that someone

00:12:24.850 --> 00:12:27.480
could love their country but
not agree with them.

00:12:27.480 --> 00:12:32.150
And can you bring yourself to
swim against the tide of all

00:12:32.150 --> 00:12:34.240
your fellows?

00:12:34.240 --> 00:12:38.520
Can you keep yourself with your
own opinions and your own

00:12:38.520 --> 00:12:40.680
ethics, your own morals,
regardless of

00:12:40.680 --> 00:12:42.000
the tide of the times?

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:45.360
And the Bush administration
was--

00:12:45.360 --> 00:12:47.820
so many people got swept in the
wrong direction, I think.

00:12:47.820 --> 00:12:48.840
ERIC SCHMIDT: And what
was interesting was--

00:12:48.840 --> 00:12:51.710
I was in the audience when you
gave the speech at the

00:12:51.710 --> 00:12:52.240
correspondents' dinner.

00:12:52.240 --> 00:12:53.180
STEPHEN COLBERT: Oh,
you were there?

00:12:53.180 --> 00:12:53.690
ERIC SCHMIDT: Yes.

00:12:53.690 --> 00:12:55.916
STEPHEN COLBERT: OK.

00:12:55.916 --> 00:12:57.620
ERIC SCHMIDT: You know, I
have nothing else to do.

00:12:57.620 --> 00:12:59.990
And so I was sitting there.

00:12:59.990 --> 00:13:04.730
And I was shocked that they were
foolish enough to invite

00:13:04.730 --> 00:13:08.970
you, because you were so good.

00:13:08.970 --> 00:13:12.380
And I think that performance
put you from sort of a

00:13:12.380 --> 00:13:16.120
specialized service to a
truly national figure.

00:13:16.120 --> 00:13:16.770
That's my opinion.

00:13:16.770 --> 00:13:18.740
I think it literally
changed the

00:13:18.740 --> 00:13:21.300
perception of you in society.

00:13:21.300 --> 00:13:23.925
STEPHEN COLBERT: I went from
boutique to chain store at

00:13:23.925 --> 00:13:25.000
that point, I guess.

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:27.780
ERIC SCHMIDT: It was like
a step function.

00:13:27.780 --> 00:13:28.405
STEPHEN COLBERT: What's
a step function?

00:13:28.405 --> 00:13:29.870
What's a step function?

00:13:29.870 --> 00:13:31.085
ERIC SCHMIDT: It's a big jump.

00:13:31.085 --> 00:13:31.810
STEPHEN COLBERT: Oh, OK.

00:13:31.810 --> 00:13:32.090
Sure.

00:13:32.090 --> 00:13:35.700
ERIC SCHMIDT: It's a
mathematical term.

00:13:35.700 --> 00:13:36.630
STEPHEN COLBERT: Like
the number line?

00:13:36.630 --> 00:13:37.300
Like the number line?

00:13:37.300 --> 00:13:38.890
Is that what you mean by math?

00:13:38.890 --> 00:13:40.180
ERIC SCHMIDT: That's
what we do.

00:13:40.180 --> 00:13:41.300
STEPHEN COLBERT: Number line,
I got the number line down.

00:13:41.300 --> 00:13:44.936
ERIC SCHMIDT: So it was like a
really big discontinuous jump.

00:13:44.936 --> 00:13:48.370
And why do you think
they invited you?

00:13:48.370 --> 00:13:52.222
Did they know what they were
getting themselves into?

00:13:52.222 --> 00:13:54.114
[THUD]

00:13:54.114 --> 00:13:56.490
[LAUGHTER]

00:13:56.490 --> 00:13:59.440
STEPHEN COLBERT: They're
coming for me.

00:13:59.440 --> 00:14:00.180
I've been waiting.

00:14:00.180 --> 00:14:01.110
I've been waiting.

00:14:01.110 --> 00:14:03.680
I did peer through the
blinds for a couple

00:14:03.680 --> 00:14:06.650
weeks after that show.

00:14:06.650 --> 00:14:08.850
I got invited really early.

00:14:08.850 --> 00:14:12.930
The show started on
October 17, 2005.

00:14:12.930 --> 00:14:13.790
And--

00:14:13.790 --> 00:14:17.690
[BEEPING]

00:14:17.690 --> 00:14:18.260
STEPHEN COLBERT: All right.

00:14:18.260 --> 00:14:20.710
ERIC SCHMIDT: So this building
was used by the Port Authority

00:14:20.710 --> 00:14:22.620
to bring buses up and down.

00:14:22.620 --> 00:14:24.660
Those are the bus--

00:14:24.660 --> 00:14:25.000
STEPHEN COLBERT: Lifts.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:25.600
ERIC SCHMIDT: --elevators.

00:14:25.600 --> 00:14:31.150
So there's a truck about to come
in and destroy us all.

00:14:31.150 --> 00:14:31.400
STEPHEN COLBERT: Good.

00:14:31.400 --> 00:14:32.205
ERIC SCHMIDT: It's backing up.

00:14:32.205 --> 00:14:32.960
That's the backing up sound.

00:14:32.960 --> 00:14:35.340
STEPHEN COLBERT: Well, I'm glad
to be here with you at

00:14:35.340 --> 00:14:38.200
the end, Eric Schmidt.

00:14:38.200 --> 00:14:42.410
ERIC SCHMIDT: I thought the
end was on December 21.

00:14:42.410 --> 00:14:43.330
STEPHEN COLBERT:
Probably, yeah.

00:14:43.330 --> 00:14:43.695
Probably.

00:14:43.695 --> 00:14:44.060
Yeah.

00:14:44.060 --> 00:14:44.300
Yeah.

00:14:44.300 --> 00:14:45.810
Though I've-- yeah, probably.

00:14:45.810 --> 00:14:49.280
ERIC SCHMIDT: No need to plan
for anything on December 22 in

00:14:49.280 --> 00:14:51.840
the Mayan calendar.

00:14:51.840 --> 00:14:54.720
Getting me back to President
Bush, who we've conveniently

00:14:54.720 --> 00:14:55.330
forgotten--

00:14:55.330 --> 00:14:56.140
STEPHEN COLBERT: Well,
I was invited

00:14:56.140 --> 00:14:57.710
by the press, actually.

00:14:57.710 --> 00:14:59.420
For the correspondents' dinner,
you are invited by

00:14:59.420 --> 00:15:00.660
whoever is the head
of the White House

00:15:00.660 --> 00:15:01.310
press corps that year.

00:15:01.310 --> 00:15:02.250
And it was a guy named--

00:15:02.250 --> 00:15:07.050
I think it's Mark Smith was the
guy from the AP, I think.

00:15:07.050 --> 00:15:09.180
And he invited me.

00:15:09.180 --> 00:15:10.270
And we were only a few
months into the show.

00:15:10.270 --> 00:15:12.420
We started in October
17, 2005.

00:15:12.420 --> 00:15:14.720
And it was January, I think, or
early February when I got

00:15:14.720 --> 00:15:15.890
the invitation.

00:15:15.890 --> 00:15:19.970
And I said to my agent,
James Dixon--

00:15:19.970 --> 00:15:20.860
I said, let me call him back.

00:15:20.860 --> 00:15:22.360
Let me call him back.

00:15:22.360 --> 00:15:23.550
And I said, I think
I want to do this.

00:15:23.550 --> 00:15:24.550
I'm going to call him back.

00:15:24.550 --> 00:15:26.810
And I called Jon Stewart
immediately.

00:15:26.810 --> 00:15:28.820
And I said, hey, Jon.

00:15:28.820 --> 00:15:31.210
I got invited down to the
correspondents' dinner.

00:15:31.210 --> 00:15:31.850
What do you think?

00:15:31.850 --> 00:15:32.320
What do you think?

00:15:32.320 --> 00:15:34.050
And he goes, to be a guest?

00:15:34.050 --> 00:15:35.260
What you mean?

00:15:35.260 --> 00:15:37.180
And I said, no, they want
me to be the guy.

00:15:37.180 --> 00:15:38.578
And he goes, what?

00:15:41.840 --> 00:15:44.550
Have they ever seen your show?

00:15:44.550 --> 00:15:46.800
And I said, I don't know.

00:15:46.800 --> 00:15:50.520
I said, I'm not going to ask.

00:15:50.520 --> 00:15:52.510
And I said, I think I kind
of got to do it.

00:15:52.510 --> 00:15:54.720
And he goes, you've
got to do it.

00:15:54.720 --> 00:15:58.000
And then we were
really worried.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:15:59.600
I knew I'd never get this
opportunity again.

00:15:59.600 --> 00:16:02.090
No one's ever going
to ask me back.

00:16:02.090 --> 00:16:06.120
But about two weeks out, we
started working on it

00:16:06.120 --> 00:16:06.930
about a month out.

00:16:06.930 --> 00:16:11.730
And the very first joke we wrote
for it was, people say

00:16:11.730 --> 00:16:15.620
that this administration is just
rearranging deck chairs

00:16:15.620 --> 00:16:16.630
on the Titanic.

00:16:16.630 --> 00:16:18.180
That is wrong.

00:16:18.180 --> 00:16:20.190
They are not sinking,
they are soaring.

00:16:20.190 --> 00:16:22.110
If anything, they are
rearranging the deck chairs on

00:16:22.110 --> 00:16:24.630
the Hindenburg.

00:16:24.630 --> 00:16:27.090
And to me, that was the spirit
of the entire thing.

00:16:27.090 --> 00:16:29.110
Like, how positive
could we be--

00:16:29.110 --> 00:16:29.970
[JABBING SOUNDS]

00:16:29.970 --> 00:16:31.690
STEPHEN COLBERT: --while
they knife them?

00:16:31.690 --> 00:16:32.720
And the press too.

00:16:32.720 --> 00:16:33.730
And the press too, of course.

00:16:33.730 --> 00:16:36.450
Because people forget that
we did 10 minutes on the

00:16:36.450 --> 00:16:38.740
administration, 10 minutes
on the press.

00:16:38.740 --> 00:16:41.840
But anyway, about three days
before I went down there, we'd

00:16:41.840 --> 00:16:42.220
been working.

00:16:42.220 --> 00:16:43.930
We do 161 shows a year.

00:16:43.930 --> 00:16:45.860
And we pulled very long weeks.

00:16:45.860 --> 00:16:48.580
As I was saying before,
65, 70 hour weeks.

00:16:48.580 --> 00:16:50.340
And we were super tired.

00:16:50.340 --> 00:16:51.520
You guys know what that's
like, I'm sure.

00:16:51.520 --> 00:16:56.310
And I go in, I get my coffee
from a very nice woman who was

00:16:56.310 --> 00:16:57.980
from Algeria.

00:16:57.980 --> 00:17:00.810
And I walked into her
coffee shop right

00:17:00.810 --> 00:17:01.540
before I went down there.

00:17:01.540 --> 00:17:02.020
And she goes, (ALGERIAN
ACCENT) oh,

00:17:02.020 --> 00:17:03.740
babies, you're so tired.

00:17:03.740 --> 00:17:04.660
What's wrong?

00:17:04.660 --> 00:17:06.170
And this is my Algerian
accent.

00:17:06.170 --> 00:17:09.950
And I told her what
I was working on.

00:17:09.950 --> 00:17:13.280
She goes, you're performing
for the president?

00:17:13.280 --> 00:17:14.819
I said, yes.

00:17:14.819 --> 00:17:16.359
And I go, he's going to be five
feet away from me the

00:17:16.359 --> 00:17:17.319
whole time.

00:17:17.319 --> 00:17:22.119
And she said, but you
are, uh, a critic.

00:17:22.119 --> 00:17:22.900
You're a critic.

00:17:22.900 --> 00:17:23.819
And I said, yes.

00:17:23.819 --> 00:17:27.960
But I get to do my jokes
just right at him.

00:17:27.960 --> 00:17:29.540
And she leaned across.

00:17:29.540 --> 00:17:31.470
She's a little lady,
very cute.

00:17:31.470 --> 00:17:33.110
And she leans across
the counter.

00:17:33.110 --> 00:17:35.600
And she took my chin
in her hand.

00:17:35.600 --> 00:17:38.810
And she said, it's
a good country.

00:17:38.810 --> 00:17:39.730
And I said, yeah.

00:17:39.730 --> 00:17:40.260
It sure is.

00:17:40.260 --> 00:17:42.480
And I told that story
to the President.

00:17:42.480 --> 00:17:45.140
Because there's a party before
the correspondents' dinner

00:17:45.140 --> 00:17:46.240
that's really great.

00:17:46.240 --> 00:17:48.580
It's you, some cabinet members,
heads of several

00:17:48.580 --> 00:17:51.520
press organizations,
and the President.

00:17:51.520 --> 00:17:52.320
And my family was there.

00:17:52.320 --> 00:17:54.290
And my mother loved
President Bush.

00:17:54.290 --> 00:17:55.750
He couldn't have been
nicer to my mom.

00:17:55.750 --> 00:17:57.730
It was really a charming
party.

00:17:57.730 --> 00:18:01.450
And I told him that story.

00:18:01.450 --> 00:18:03.500
Because he goes, it's
nice we can do this.

00:18:03.500 --> 00:18:04.940
And I told him the story.

00:18:04.940 --> 00:18:07.250
And he goes, only in America.

00:18:07.250 --> 00:18:13.600
And it was a very positive kind
of vibe that lasted for

00:18:13.600 --> 00:18:14.850
about another hour.

00:18:17.900 --> 00:18:18.370
It was fun.

00:18:18.370 --> 00:18:19.820
It was a really fun night.

00:18:19.820 --> 00:18:21.270
ERIC SCHMIDT: But
from that point,

00:18:21.270 --> 00:18:22.700
something happened in America.

00:18:22.700 --> 00:18:27.290
You and Jon Stewart actually
became the major political

00:18:27.290 --> 00:18:29.120
operatives, whether you
like it or not.

00:18:29.120 --> 00:18:30.090
STEPHEN COLBERT: I don't.

00:18:30.090 --> 00:18:30.960
ERIC SCHMIDT: Well, trust me.

00:18:30.960 --> 00:18:31.600
STEPHEN COLBERT: Because
I'm a comedian.

00:18:31.600 --> 00:18:32.390
I'm not a political operative.

00:18:32.390 --> 00:18:34.140
I make jokes about the news.

00:18:34.140 --> 00:18:35.900
A lot of the news is
about politics.

00:18:35.900 --> 00:18:37.770
That's not my fault.

00:18:37.770 --> 00:18:38.200
ERIC SCHMIDT: OK.

00:18:38.200 --> 00:18:40.000
STEPHEN COLBERT: Do you
know what I mean?

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:43.280
Political operative means that
you have some gain beyond what

00:18:43.280 --> 00:18:43.690
you're doing.

00:18:43.690 --> 00:18:46.770
Politics itself means I am not
telling you my intention.

00:18:46.770 --> 00:18:49.250
I am showing you an action that
is causing a reaction

00:18:49.250 --> 00:18:51.870
from you while I'm playing
another chess piece over here.

00:18:51.870 --> 00:18:55.150
And together I will triangulate
some secretive way

00:18:55.150 --> 00:18:58.010
where I will achieve
power over you.

