Or if you'd like me to do
something, I can try to make

00:29:21.530 --> 00:29:24.010
time for it if it still sounds
like it's going to be fun or

00:29:24.010 --> 00:29:25.430
challenging or something
like that.

00:29:25.430 --> 00:29:28.470
But seven years, eight years,
something like that.

00:29:28.470 --> 00:29:29.710
I don't mind auditioning.

00:29:29.710 --> 00:29:30.450
I really don't.

00:29:30.450 --> 00:29:32.620
Because if I was on the other
side, I would definitely want

00:29:32.620 --> 00:29:34.350
to know whether the
guy could do it.

00:29:34.350 --> 00:29:36.780
I don't want to hire somebody
because they're famous or

00:29:36.780 --> 00:29:37.930
really handsome.

00:29:37.930 --> 00:29:40.870
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:29:40.870 --> 00:29:41.850
Thanks.

00:29:41.850 --> 00:29:43.590
ERIC SCHMIDT: You have
a question over here.

00:29:43.590 --> 00:29:49.650
Meanwhile, I'll ask you how do
you think Google can become

00:29:49.650 --> 00:29:51.170
the greatness that
we never weren't?

00:29:56.690 --> 00:29:59.270
STEPHEN COLBERT: It kind
of already is.

00:29:59.270 --> 00:30:01.560
And I'm not trying to blow
secondhand smoke up your butt.

00:30:04.510 --> 00:30:05.760
Google can be anything
you want it to be.

00:30:05.760 --> 00:30:08.380
Because it's a reflection
of your own desire.

00:30:08.380 --> 00:30:11.130
It's a porthole toward what
you want it to be.

00:30:11.130 --> 00:30:15.060
Unless you guys are putting
some restricters on the

00:30:15.060 --> 00:30:18.660
information that I think I'm
getting, then it is anything

00:30:18.660 --> 00:30:19.810
we want it to be.

00:30:19.810 --> 00:30:22.240
Because it's an actuator.

00:30:22.240 --> 00:30:28.330
Or it's a pathway to what we
want, rather than the thing we

00:30:28.330 --> 00:30:29.050
want itself.

00:30:29.050 --> 00:30:29.760
Do you know what I mean?

00:30:29.760 --> 00:30:33.065
So it's the finger that allows
us to look at the moon.

00:30:35.655 --> 00:30:36.860
ERIC SCHMIDT: Good.

00:30:36.860 --> 00:30:37.540
We'll take that.

00:30:37.540 --> 00:30:38.130
STEPHEN COLBERT: You
know what I mean?

00:30:38.130 --> 00:30:40.280
Don't look at my finger.

00:30:40.280 --> 00:30:41.280
You'll miss out on all that--

00:30:41.280 --> 00:30:42.020
ERIC SCHMIDT: Everyone
understood that's the

00:30:42.020 --> 00:30:42.870
strategic [INAUDIBLE].

00:30:42.870 --> 00:30:43.890
Go ahead.

00:30:43.890 --> 00:30:44.580
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:30:44.580 --> 00:30:47.060
This is a few years ago, but
what actually happened between

00:30:47.060 --> 00:30:48.440
you and "The Venture
Bros." guys?

00:30:48.440 --> 00:30:50.520
Is there bad blood there, or was
there a miscommunication?

00:30:50.520 --> 00:30:53.030
STEPHEN COLBERT: No, I can't
do my show and do that.

00:30:53.030 --> 00:30:54.790
I also had to quit "Harvey
Birdman," too.

00:30:54.790 --> 00:30:57.470
I just couldn't do my show
and do the voiceovers.

00:30:57.470 --> 00:31:01.430
Because I think "The Venture
Bros." was great.

00:31:01.430 --> 00:31:05.940
And I loved doing "Harvey
Birdman." But they had to wait

00:31:05.940 --> 00:31:07.170
for me too much.

00:31:07.170 --> 00:31:07.810
Do you know what I mean?

00:31:07.810 --> 00:31:10.340
I eventually couldn't do
any of it anymore.

00:31:10.340 --> 00:31:12.940
When I had to quit "Harvey
Birdman," I played a guy named

00:31:12.940 --> 00:31:14.310
Phil Ken Sebben and a
guy named Reducto.

00:31:14.310 --> 00:31:15.900
And Phil Ken Sebben would
say things like,

00:31:15.900 --> 00:31:17.820
haha, bobbly parts.

00:31:17.820 --> 00:31:22.310
And when both of them died on
one show-- they were both hit

00:31:22.310 --> 00:31:25.850
by a bus on the same corner at
different parts of the same

00:31:25.850 --> 00:31:27.550
cartoon by the same bus.

00:31:27.550 --> 00:31:30.600
And if you freeze the frame at
the moment that I get hit, my

00:31:30.600 --> 00:31:32.520
characters get hit, on the
side of the bus, it says,

00:31:32.520 --> 00:31:36.480
watch "The Colbert Report,"
11:30 on Comedy Central.

00:31:36.480 --> 00:31:37.840
But no, there's no bad blood.

00:31:37.840 --> 00:31:38.600
I think they're both great.

00:31:38.600 --> 00:31:39.110
AUDIENCE: Cool.

00:31:39.110 --> 00:31:41.310
Thanks.

00:31:41.310 --> 00:31:44.080
ERIC SCHMIDT: Employees have
submitted questions online.

00:31:44.080 --> 00:31:46.115
Here's one that I'm not quite
sure how to interpret.

00:31:46.115 --> 00:31:48.115
So I'll just read it to you.

00:31:48.115 --> 00:31:48.590
STEPHEN COLBERT: Sure.

00:31:48.590 --> 00:31:49.740
ERIC SCHMIDT: "Would
you rather fight

00:31:49.740 --> 00:31:52.180
one horse-sized duck"--

00:31:52.180 --> 00:31:52.790
STEPHEN COLBERT: Or one
duck-sized horse.

00:31:52.790 --> 00:31:54.765
ERIC SCHMIDT: --"or 100
duck-sized horses?"

00:31:54.765 --> 00:31:55.160
STEPHEN COLBERT: Yeah.

00:31:55.160 --> 00:31:55.638
Yeah.

00:31:55.638 --> 00:31:56.116
Yeah.

00:31:56.116 --> 00:31:57.366
Yeah.

00:32:05.210 --> 00:32:07.140
100 duck-sized horses,
I would say.

00:32:07.140 --> 00:32:08.080
100 duck sized horses.

00:32:08.080 --> 00:32:08.990
ERIC SCHMIDT: You heard
it here first.

00:32:08.990 --> 00:32:10.080
That's a clear answer.

00:32:10.080 --> 00:32:11.040
STEPHEN COLBERT: That's
a clear answer.

00:32:11.040 --> 00:32:13.100
Did I win?

00:32:13.100 --> 00:32:14.620
Is there a right answer there?

00:32:14.620 --> 00:32:15.460
ERIC SCHMIDT: I'm
sure there is.

00:32:15.460 --> 00:32:16.030
STEPHEN COLBERT:
How about you?

00:32:16.030 --> 00:32:16.890
What would you rather do?

00:32:16.890 --> 00:32:18.910
ERIC SCHMIDT: I would
pick the opposite.

00:32:18.910 --> 00:32:21.500
STEPHEN COLBERT: A
horse sized duck?

00:32:21.500 --> 00:32:24.600
Are you insane?

00:32:24.600 --> 00:32:27.440
I mean, it's not a sharp
beak but one blow.

00:32:27.440 --> 00:32:29.940
The thing has got to weigh
like 1,200 pounds.

00:32:29.940 --> 00:32:33.980
Whereas duck-sized horses, you
could just snap their spines

00:32:33.980 --> 00:32:36.170
as they came at you.

00:32:36.170 --> 00:32:38.010
What I don't understand is,
why are we fighting them?

00:32:40.870 --> 00:32:41.620
Wait a second.

00:32:41.620 --> 00:32:42.770
I know why I'm right.

00:32:42.770 --> 00:32:43.760
I know why I'm right.

00:32:43.760 --> 00:32:48.370
Because horses are vegetarian,
and ducks are carnivores.

00:32:48.370 --> 00:32:49.630
The duck would come at you.

00:32:49.630 --> 00:32:51.520
And the horses essentially would
leave you alone unless

00:32:51.520 --> 00:32:54.410
your pockets were
filled with hay.

00:32:54.410 --> 00:32:55.380
ERIC SCHMIDT: Which
they are not.

00:32:55.380 --> 00:32:57.880
STEPHEN COLBERT: Which they are
not, as far as we know.

00:32:57.880 --> 00:32:58.510
ERIC SCHMIDT: OK.

00:32:58.510 --> 00:32:59.780
That's a very clear answer.

00:32:59.780 --> 00:33:01.110
Yes, ma'am?

00:33:01.110 --> 00:33:03.620
AUDIENCE: Can you recall a
time that you were struck

00:33:03.620 --> 00:33:05.700
speechless?

00:33:05.700 --> 00:33:07.110
STEPHEN COLBERT: Yes.

00:33:07.110 --> 00:33:10.320
Several, but the one that leaps
to mind immediately was

00:33:10.320 --> 00:33:13.110
when I had Jane Fonda
on the show.

00:33:13.110 --> 00:33:19.380
And without preamble, she got
up, sat on my lap, and stuck

00:33:19.380 --> 00:33:20.630
her tongue in my ear.

00:33:24.170 --> 00:33:25.370
And I was rigid.

00:33:25.370 --> 00:33:28.080
I didn't know what to do.

00:33:28.080 --> 00:33:31.220
And if anyone's old enough to
remember Johnny Carson, there

00:33:31.220 --> 00:33:33.850
was the famous time when a
spider monkey crawled on top

00:33:33.850 --> 00:33:34.950
of his head.

00:33:34.950 --> 00:33:36.750
He was having Jack Hanna on.

00:33:36.750 --> 00:33:38.240
And a spider monkey jumped
on his head.

00:33:38.240 --> 00:33:43.650
And I thought, Jane Fonda
is my spider monkey.

00:33:43.650 --> 00:33:45.290
I don't know what to
do with myself.

00:33:49.580 --> 00:33:51.930
ERIC SCHMIDT: Googlers have
continued to suggest important

00:33:51.930 --> 00:33:54.910
questions as a follow up to the
duck versus horse debate.

00:33:54.910 --> 00:33:55.400
STEPHEN COLBERT: Oh, really?

00:33:55.400 --> 00:33:56.010
ERIC SCHMIDT: Yes.

00:33:56.010 --> 00:33:56.800
Here's the next one.

00:33:56.800 --> 00:33:57.740
STEPHEN COLBERT:
As a follow up?

00:33:57.740 --> 00:33:58.480
ERIC SCHMIDT: Yes.

00:33:58.480 --> 00:34:01.010
STEPHEN COLBERT: From my answer,
on a piece of paper?

00:34:01.010 --> 00:34:04.460
Google's that good that they're
actually transmitting

00:34:04.460 --> 00:34:07.490
onto a piece of paper
right now?

00:34:07.490 --> 00:34:09.380
Why are you withholding
that technology

00:34:09.380 --> 00:34:10.710
from the rest of us?

00:34:10.710 --> 00:34:12.320
ERIC SCHMIDT: We really are.

00:34:12.320 --> 00:34:12.960
STEPHEN COLBERT: Wow.

00:34:12.960 --> 00:34:15.530
ERIC SCHMIDT: "What are your
plans for welcoming the royal

00:34:15.530 --> 00:34:18.520
baby?" This is the question.

00:34:18.520 --> 00:34:19.580
I'm sorry.

00:34:19.580 --> 00:34:27.400
"Any suggestions to what the
baby should be named?"

00:34:27.400 --> 00:34:28.710
STEPHEN COLBERT: Stephen
Colbert's got a nice ring to

00:34:28.710 --> 00:34:30.790
it, obviously.

00:34:30.790 --> 00:34:35.770
Charles Phillip Arthur George,
George Phillip Arthur Charles,

00:34:35.770 --> 00:34:39.150
Arthur Phillip Charles George.

00:34:39.150 --> 00:34:40.199
ERIC SCHMIDT: All four?

00:34:40.199 --> 00:34:41.150
STEPHEN COLBERT: Any
one of those.

00:34:41.150 --> 00:34:42.120
ERIC SCHMIDT: In
whatever order?

00:34:42.120 --> 00:34:42.739
STEPHEN COLBERT: Sure.

00:34:42.739 --> 00:34:43.110
Sure.

00:34:43.110 --> 00:34:46.670
If there's an infinite
number of four names.

00:34:46.670 --> 00:34:48.699
ERIC SCHMIDT: There are,
well, 2 to the 4th.

00:34:48.699 --> 00:34:49.600
STEPHEN COLBERT: 16
or something.

00:34:49.600 --> 00:34:50.969
2 to the 4 or whatever
you said.

00:34:50.969 --> 00:34:51.889
ERIC SCHMIDT: 4 times
3 times 2.

00:34:51.889 --> 00:34:52.100
STEPHEN COLBERT: Something
like that.

00:34:52.100 --> 00:34:52.510
Whatever.

00:34:52.510 --> 00:34:54.073
I don't know.

00:34:54.073 --> 00:34:55.474
I don't know.

00:34:55.474 --> 00:34:56.875
I don't know.

00:34:56.875 --> 00:34:57.342
Yeah.

00:34:57.342 --> 00:34:57.809
ERIC SCHMIDT: OK.

00:34:57.809 --> 00:34:58.280
STEPHEN COLBERT: Yeah.

00:34:58.280 --> 00:35:00.275
Again, the number line.

00:35:00.275 --> 00:35:00.990
The number line.

00:35:00.990 --> 00:35:02.370
That's what I liked
when I was a kid.

00:35:02.370 --> 00:35:04.580
No matter what class you were
in, whether you were in first

00:35:04.580 --> 00:35:08.560
grade or if you were in
calculus, the book starts with

00:35:08.560 --> 00:35:09.870
the number line.

00:35:09.870 --> 00:35:12.770
First pages is let's remind
ourselves what integers are.

00:35:12.770 --> 00:35:13.580
ERIC SCHMIDT: Another
Google has asked--

00:35:13.580 --> 00:35:15.210
STEPHEN COLBERT: That was the
middle of a sentence just now.

00:35:15.210 --> 00:35:16.460
ERIC SCHMIDT: OK.

00:35:18.970 --> 00:35:19.950
Another Googler has asked--

00:35:19.950 --> 00:35:22.350
STEPHEN COLBERT: You people
have to put up with this.

00:35:22.350 --> 00:35:24.090
I'm so sorry.

00:35:24.090 --> 00:35:27.260
Power mad, is what I
would describe you.

00:35:27.260 --> 00:35:28.770
ERIC SCHMIDT: Googlers have
asked, "How would you

00:35:28.770 --> 00:35:31.420
officially determine if
a tree is balanced?

00:35:31.420 --> 00:35:38.250
What is the runtime of your
algorithm?" For your benefit--

00:35:38.250 --> 00:35:39.610
STEPHEN COLBERT: If a
tree is balanced--

00:35:39.610 --> 00:35:43.840
a tree is balanced if you
can hang ornaments

00:35:43.840 --> 00:35:45.090
on any part of it.

00:35:47.605 --> 00:35:49.036
ERIC SCHMIDT: That's a
very good argument.

00:35:52.380 --> 00:35:53.240
Did you have a question?

00:35:53.240 --> 00:35:54.400
Yes, go ahead.

00:35:54.400 --> 00:35:56.060
AUDIENCE: What is the difference
between Stephen

00:35:56.060 --> 00:35:57.610
Colbert, the person,
and Stephen

00:35:57.610 --> 00:35:59.070
Colbert, the character?

00:35:59.070 --> 00:36:02.260
And what were the challenges
in you becoming Stephen

00:36:02.260 --> 00:36:05.020
Colbert, the character?

00:36:05.020 --> 00:36:07.210
STEPHEN COLBERT: There are a
lot of differences, I hope,

00:36:07.210 --> 00:36:09.860
between me and my character.

00:36:09.860 --> 00:36:14.000
I mean, there are some things
we have in common.

00:36:14.000 --> 00:36:16.190
We're both from South
Carolina.

00:36:16.190 --> 00:36:18.690
We're both fans of
Tolkien's work.

00:36:18.690 --> 00:36:20.190
Though, I tried to keep that
separate at first.

00:36:20.190 --> 00:36:21.530
I tried to keep that membrane.

00:36:21.530 --> 00:36:23.090
At first I was like,
no, no, no.

00:36:23.090 --> 00:36:23.840
That's too important to me.

00:36:23.840 --> 00:36:25.340
I don't want him to have that.

00:36:25.340 --> 00:36:27.540
But there were too many
opportunities for me

00:36:27.540 --> 00:36:28.510
to wax about it.

00:36:28.510 --> 00:36:33.430
So I went ahead and let that
membrane be permeable.

00:36:33.430 --> 00:36:37.370
But we're both super
Catholics.

00:36:37.370 --> 00:36:40.250
He thinks he's Captain
Catholic.

00:36:40.250 --> 00:36:42.480
I still go to church.

00:36:42.480 --> 00:36:47.870
And I'm not a particularly
pious or devout Catholic.

00:36:47.870 --> 00:36:49.120
Though I still go.

00:36:51.420 --> 00:36:54.850
He's a well-intentioned, poorly

00:36:54.850 --> 00:36:58.440
informed, high status idiot.

00:36:58.440 --> 00:37:01.370
And I'd like to think I'm
well-intentioned.

00:37:01.370 --> 00:37:03.730
I'm better informed
than he is.

00:37:03.730 --> 00:37:06.375
He is completely incurious
about the world.

00:37:06.375 --> 00:37:09.940
He is living an unexamined
life.

00:37:09.940 --> 00:37:12.970
And that's fine with him.

00:37:12.970 --> 00:37:14.100
He's high status.

00:37:14.100 --> 00:37:15.810
I really enjoy being
low status.

00:37:15.810 --> 00:37:19.180
I really enjoy playing
a weak character.

00:37:19.180 --> 00:37:22.180
That's why I really enjoy
him is that he is this

00:37:22.180 --> 00:37:23.750
unbelievably self-important
character.

00:37:23.750 --> 00:37:26.560
In fact, Jim Fenhagen,
who designed the

00:37:26.560 --> 00:37:27.840
Republican set this year.

00:37:27.840 --> 00:37:29.540
And he does the Olympics.

00:37:29.540 --> 00:37:30.555
He's a huge set designer.

00:37:30.555 --> 00:37:32.470
And he's a wonderful guy,
an old friend of mine.

00:37:32.470 --> 00:37:34.260
I said to him-- when he was
designing my first set, I

00:37:34.260 --> 00:37:36.960
said, I want your inspiration
to be da Vinci's "Last

00:37:36.960 --> 00:37:41.100
Supper." Because if you look at
da Vinci's "Last Supper,"

00:37:41.100 --> 00:37:42.710
Christ has no halo.

00:37:42.710 --> 00:37:44.810
Existence, all of creation
is his halo.

00:37:44.810 --> 00:37:46.890
Because there are all these
converging lines in the room.

00:37:46.890 --> 00:37:51.000
And in reality, they converge
upon Christ's head.

00:37:51.000 --> 00:37:52.790
As the world is God's
foot stool--

00:37:52.790 --> 00:37:54.070
as it says in Matthew--

00:37:54.070 --> 00:37:57.120
the world is Christ's halo.

00:37:57.120 --> 00:37:59.070
And so I said, I want my
whole set to be like

00:37:59.070 --> 00:38:00.250
a halo around me.

00:38:00.250 --> 00:38:01.680
So if you looked at my original
set, there were these

00:38:01.680 --> 00:38:03.290
convergent lines that
come out of my set.

00:38:03.290 --> 00:38:07.480
And we painted it on the floor
so I am the rising sun.

00:38:07.480 --> 00:38:09.770
There are no television
monitors behind me.

00:38:09.770 --> 00:38:12.520
I'm not like what Brian
Williams' or even Jon's set.

00:38:12.520 --> 00:38:14.190
He's got television monitors
behind him.

00:38:14.190 --> 00:38:15.540
And he's conveying
the news to you.

00:38:15.540 --> 00:38:16.780
He is a conduit.

00:38:16.780 --> 00:38:18.880
I am the news.

00:38:18.880 --> 00:38:22.360
I am a dawn onto my own day.

00:38:22.360 --> 00:38:25.750
But that's the outward status
of the character.

00:38:25.750 --> 00:38:28.860
But his weakness and his
incuriousness and his thin

00:38:28.860 --> 00:38:31.970
skinned quality weakens him
in such wonderful ways.

00:38:31.970 --> 00:38:33.970
And I love that weakness,
because I think that's the

00:38:33.970 --> 00:38:34.780
reality of me.

00:38:34.780 --> 00:38:41.460
I think I'm not as well
defined and as he is.

00:38:41.460 --> 00:38:44.755
And I enjoy copping to that
in my own behavior.

00:38:48.010 --> 00:38:49.340
ERIC SCHMIDT: What's
interesting about--

00:38:49.340 --> 00:38:52.285
I think there is union in your
character and you personally.

00:38:52.285 --> 00:38:54.880
You're very supportive
of the troops.

00:38:54.880 --> 00:38:57.945
And I remember when you were in
Iraq, you got the president

00:38:57.945 --> 00:38:59.630
to order you to get a haircut.

00:38:59.630 --> 00:39:00.370
STEPHEN COLBERT: Yeah.

00:39:00.370 --> 00:39:01.190
ERIC SCHMIDT: Pretty serious.

00:39:01.190 --> 00:39:01.390
STEPHEN COLBERT: That was fun.

00:39:01.390 --> 00:39:01.610
Yeah.

00:39:01.610 --> 00:39:03.440
Sure, yeah.

00:39:03.440 --> 00:39:05.980
I knew I wanted to have my
head shaved, because I

00:39:05.980 --> 00:39:08.825
thought, oh, that'll feel
good in the room.

00:39:08.825 --> 00:39:11.050
That'll feel good with
all the troops.

00:39:11.050 --> 00:39:12.490
And I said, who could
shave my head?

00:39:12.490 --> 00:39:13.470
The general.

00:39:13.470 --> 00:39:14.760
Well, who's going to make
the general do it?

00:39:14.760 --> 00:39:16.590
The president.

00:39:16.590 --> 00:39:17.570
And everybody said yes.

00:39:17.570 --> 00:39:19.540
It was really lovely.

00:39:19.540 --> 00:39:20.840
ERIC SCHMIDT: And I think this
work that you're doing with

00:39:20.840 --> 00:39:22.970
the troops is fantastic.

00:39:22.970 --> 00:39:25.170
Was there some reason in growing
up or something that

00:39:25.170 --> 00:39:25.750
you felt that way?

00:39:25.750 --> 00:39:27.090
Or is it just you're
just a genuine

00:39:27.090 --> 00:39:29.580
patriot about this stuff?

00:39:29.580 --> 00:39:30.500
STEPHEN COLBERT: I don't know.

00:39:30.500 --> 00:39:32.490
I'm a genuine patriot.

00:39:32.490 --> 00:39:33.200
I love my country.

00:39:33.200 --> 00:39:36.320
And I think patriotism
does not require

00:39:36.320 --> 00:39:37.590
focus on the troops.

00:39:37.590 --> 00:39:38.180
Do you know what I mean?

00:39:38.180 --> 00:39:40.940
There are other ways to be
patriotic other than

00:39:40.940 --> 00:39:43.420
association with the military.

00:39:43.420 --> 00:39:46.430
That being said, I think not
enough attention is paid to

00:39:46.430 --> 00:39:49.300
the men and women who make the
sacrifices that we have

00:39:49.300 --> 00:39:52.006
collectively decided they should
make and then ignore.

00:39:52.006 --> 00:39:52.352
ERIC SCHMIDT: Yes.

00:39:52.352 --> 00:39:52.910
STEPHEN COLBERT: Do you
know what I mean?

00:39:52.910 --> 00:39:53.420
ERIC SCHMIDT: I agree.

00:39:53.420 --> 00:39:54.280
STEPHEN COLBERT: We're
all responsible.

00:39:54.280 --> 00:39:58.070
We all are sending
the troop orders.

00:39:58.070 --> 00:39:59.130
Do you know what I mean?

00:39:59.130 --> 00:40:02.150
And we did it without a lot of
thought, but with a lot of

00:40:02.150 --> 00:40:07.800
emotion 10, 11 years ago, and
not a lot of discussion.

00:40:07.800 --> 00:40:10.040
And then we thought
our job was done.

00:40:10.040 --> 00:40:12.250
And so because I talk about it
a lot, or used to talk about

00:40:12.250 --> 00:40:14.010
it more when it was more in the
consciousness, especially

00:40:14.010 --> 00:40:16.970
the news consciousness, because
my show is a shadow of

00:40:16.970 --> 00:40:18.280
the actual news.

00:40:18.280 --> 00:40:21.490
And I'm, in some ways, very
reactive that way.

00:40:21.490 --> 00:40:27.930
I felt at a certain point that
I had a responsibility, along

00:40:27.930 --> 00:40:31.800
with my responsibility to be
funny, to take opportunities

00:40:31.800 --> 00:40:34.550
that came to me to talk about
the troops when I can.

00:40:34.550 --> 00:40:40.060
I have an 82nd Airborne flag
in my office because very

00:40:40.060 --> 00:40:43.110
early on in the show, a young
man and his wife came.

00:40:43.110 --> 00:40:45.120
And she had to speak for
him because he had

00:40:45.120 --> 00:40:47.040
such bad brain damage.

00:40:47.040 --> 00:40:49.260
And he still could hear.

00:40:49.260 --> 00:40:50.285
But he couldn't really
converse.

00:40:50.285 --> 00:40:51.630
And he enjoyed the show.

00:40:51.630 --> 00:40:53.150
And he gave me the flag.

00:40:53.150 --> 00:40:56.380
And all he could really get
out was, don't forget us.

00:40:56.380 --> 00:40:58.050
Please keep talking about us.

00:40:58.050 --> 00:40:58.970
So I've got it on my wall.

00:40:58.970 --> 00:40:59.730
And I think about it.

00:40:59.730 --> 00:41:01.030
And we don't nearly do enough.

00:41:01.030 --> 00:41:04.320
And we don't help as
much as we should.

00:41:04.320 --> 00:41:05.780
But certainly, when you have an

00:41:05.780 --> 00:41:07.990
opportunity that fits within--

00:41:07.990 --> 00:41:08.980
I still have the responsibility

00:41:08.980 --> 00:41:10.530
to do a comedy show.

00:41:10.530 --> 00:41:14.060
When I can fit those two things
together, we're more

00:41:14.060 --> 00:41:15.430
than happy to try to
make it happen.

00:41:15.430 --> 00:41:17.040
And as I said, we
should do more.

00:41:17.040 --> 00:41:18.610
ERIC SCHMIDT: Well, we still
have 100,000 troops in

00:41:18.610 --> 00:41:19.370
Afghanistan.

00:41:19.370 --> 00:41:20.480
STEPHEN COLBERT: Right.

00:41:20.480 --> 00:41:20.720
Right.

00:41:20.720 --> 00:41:21.550
I mean, we went to Iraq.

00:41:21.550 --> 00:41:23.880
And I'd love to be able to do
something in Afghanistan, too.

00:41:23.880 --> 00:41:26.610
And sadly, I think I might
have the time to.

00:41:26.610 --> 00:41:27.060
ERIC SCHMIDT: Yeah.

00:41:27.060 --> 00:41:28.410
Go head.

00:41:28.410 --> 00:41:30.630
AUDIENCE: So a few year's back,
you suffered a terrible

00:41:30.630 --> 00:41:33.060
work related injury
at your wrist.

00:41:33.060 --> 00:41:35.460
So my question to you is, do
you plan to expand to other

00:41:35.460 --> 00:41:38.540
body parts, like ankles, legs?

00:41:38.540 --> 00:41:41.460
STEPHEN COLBERT: Anything that
shatters, I will call

00:41:41.460 --> 00:41:42.660
attention to.

00:41:42.660 --> 00:41:43.325
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:41:43.325 --> 00:41:44.640
STEPHEN COLBERT: Anything that
happens to me-- that's the

00:41:44.640 --> 00:41:46.610
nice thing about the character
and one of the things that

00:41:46.610 --> 00:41:49.220
saves me when there's down
time in the news is that

00:41:49.220 --> 00:41:53.910
anything I think is worth
talking about is news.

00:41:53.910 --> 00:41:55.650
That's the character,
can name it.

00:41:55.650 --> 00:41:58.390
Anything that happens to me is
the most important thing

00:41:58.390 --> 00:41:59.750
that's happening right now.

00:41:59.750 --> 00:42:02.340
And when I broke my wrist, sad
to say, the first thing I

00:42:02.340 --> 00:42:03.590
thought of is content.

00:42:06.760 --> 00:42:08.000
AUDIENCE: And I have
a further question.

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:10.680
How is your auditioning of Eric
Schmidt going right now?

00:42:10.680 --> 00:42:12.880
And do you plan on taking
Eric on your book tour?

00:42:18.690 --> 00:42:20.470
STEPHEN COLBERT: He's
doing very well.

00:42:20.470 --> 00:42:22.350
He's doing very well.

00:42:22.350 --> 00:42:25.880
Do you have an up tempo
or a ballad?

00:42:25.880 --> 00:42:27.130
ERIC SCHMIDT: Oh, my god.

00:42:29.030 --> 00:42:29.165
STEPHEN COLBERT: [SINGING]

00:42:29.165 --> 00:42:32.070
I really can't stay.

00:42:32.070 --> 00:42:33.555
Baby, it's cold outside.

00:42:36.490 --> 00:42:37.450
Go ahead.

00:42:37.450 --> 00:42:38.680
Hit it.

00:42:38.680 --> 00:42:42.710
ERIC SCHMIDT: I learned
how to dance with PSY.

00:42:42.710 --> 00:42:43.410
That was enough.

00:42:43.410 --> 00:42:43.910
STEPHEN COLBERT: You did?

00:42:43.910 --> 00:42:44.570
ERIC SCHMIDT: Yes.

00:42:44.570 --> 00:42:45.380
STEPHEN COLBERT: Wow.

00:42:45.380 --> 00:42:47.430
ERIC SCHMIDT: I was
really bad.

00:42:47.430 --> 00:42:50.910
STEPHEN COLBERT: So is he.

00:42:50.910 --> 00:42:52.730
ERIC SCHMIDT: Come on, he is
the number one cultural

00:42:52.730 --> 00:42:53.960
phenomenon, 800,000,000--

00:42:53.960 --> 00:42:55.250
STEPHEN COLBERT: And if it's
popular, it must be good.

00:42:55.250 --> 00:42:56.460
ERIC SCHMIDT: Absolutely.

00:42:56.460 --> 00:42:59.180
Speaking of which, again, many
Googlers have been asking

00:42:59.180 --> 00:43:03.040
questions about your upcoming
YouTube show.

00:43:03.040 --> 00:43:05.960
STEPHEN COLBERT: Yeah,
what is that?

00:43:05.960 --> 00:43:07.090
I have an upcoming
YouTube show?

00:43:07.090 --> 00:43:09.270
ERIC SCHMIDT: Yes, we have all
decided that you have to have

00:43:09.270 --> 00:43:10.610
a YouTube show of some kind.

00:43:10.610 --> 00:43:11.770
STEPHEN COLBERT: OK.

00:43:11.770 --> 00:43:14.830
Does that violate my contract
with Viacom to have that?

00:43:14.830 --> 00:43:16.890
Because you guys had a billion
dollar lawsuit against each

00:43:16.890 --> 00:43:17.875
other, you realize.

00:43:17.875 --> 00:43:19.420
And Sumner Redstone
would rather see

00:43:19.420 --> 00:43:19.960
your head on a stick.

00:43:19.960 --> 00:43:23.460
ERIC SCHMIDT: You actually asked
us on television to give

00:43:23.460 --> 00:43:24.050
you the money.

00:43:24.050 --> 00:43:25.130
You forget.

00:43:25.130 --> 00:43:25.950
STEPHEN COLBERT: No,
I don't forget.

00:43:25.950 --> 00:43:26.980
You never gave it to me.

00:43:26.980 --> 00:43:27.910
ERIC SCHMIDT: I know.

00:43:27.910 --> 00:43:28.280
I know.

00:43:28.280 --> 00:43:28.490
We discussed--

00:43:28.490 --> 00:43:30.400
STEPHEN COLBERT: If you gave the
money, I'd be knee deep in

00:43:30.400 --> 00:43:33.744
hookers and blow,
and I'd forget.

00:43:33.744 --> 00:43:35.160
And I was deposed.

00:43:35.160 --> 00:43:36.960
I was deposed for
that lawsuit.

00:43:36.960 --> 00:43:37.770
ERIC SCHMIDT: I know you were.

00:43:37.770 --> 00:43:38.700
STEPHEN COLBERT: And I've
got a good story

00:43:38.700 --> 00:43:39.950
if you'd stop talking.

00:43:42.670 --> 00:43:43.010
I'm sorry.

00:43:43.010 --> 00:43:44.940
What was your question?

00:43:44.940 --> 00:43:45.750
ERIC SCHMIDT: Tell your story.

00:43:45.750 --> 00:43:46.135
STEPHEN COLBERT: OK.

00:43:46.135 --> 00:43:47.890
OK.

00:43:47.890 --> 00:43:48.980
So it's been a few years.

00:43:48.980 --> 00:43:50.070
I don't think I'm violating
anything.

00:43:50.070 --> 00:43:53.780
So I got deposed for the YouTube
Google thing, the

00:43:53.780 --> 00:43:54.480
Viacom thing.

00:43:54.480 --> 00:43:57.030
Because boy, they were
mad at you guys.

00:43:57.030 --> 00:43:58.320
They were so mad at you guys.

00:43:58.320 --> 00:44:02.680
And so your all's lawyer brought
me in to say, well,

00:44:02.680 --> 00:44:03.960
how isn't YouTube great?

00:44:03.960 --> 00:44:05.960
And wouldn't you not have a show
if it wasn't for YouTube?

00:44:05.960 --> 00:44:07.260
And all those kind
of questions.

00:44:07.260 --> 00:44:12.450
And the lawyer for Google would
read me statements that

00:44:12.450 --> 00:44:13.210
I said on air.

00:44:13.210 --> 00:44:15.860
And I said, well, I
didn't say that.

00:44:15.860 --> 00:44:17.730
And he goes, no, you said it.

00:44:17.730 --> 00:44:18.640
You said it on this broadcast.

00:44:18.640 --> 00:44:21.150
I said, no, my character
said that.

00:44:21.150 --> 00:44:24.520
And my character's not
under oath right now.

00:44:24.520 --> 00:44:34.260
And they said, well, if your
character were here, what

00:44:34.260 --> 00:44:36.720
would he say?

00:44:36.720 --> 00:44:41.220
And so I would say, OK, well,
I'll tell you what.

00:44:41.220 --> 00:44:41.810
I'll tell you what.

00:44:41.810 --> 00:44:45.010
If you ask me questions that my
character has to answer as

00:44:45.010 --> 00:44:49.180
opposed to me, I'll move my
coffee cup to the other side

00:44:49.180 --> 00:44:50.950
of my place here.

00:44:50.950 --> 00:44:53.340
And then you'll know I'm
speaking as my character.

00:44:53.340 --> 00:44:54.680
And so they'd ask
me a question.

00:44:54.680 --> 00:44:55.960
I'd keep my cup over here.

00:44:55.960 --> 00:44:58.060
And then in the middle of a
question, I'd start moving it

00:44:58.060 --> 00:44:59.420
over to the side.

00:44:59.420 --> 00:45:00.790
Because I realized they
were asking me

00:45:00.790 --> 00:45:02.010
something for my character.

00:45:02.010 --> 00:45:05.310
And the person would go, let
the record reflect that the

00:45:05.310 --> 00:45:07.040
coffee cup is now on the left
side of Mr. Colbert.

00:45:11.040 --> 00:45:14.090
ERIC SCHMIDT: You
have a question.

00:45:14.090 --> 00:45:15.220
STEPHEN COLBERT: My character's
answer was always

00:45:15.220 --> 00:45:20.250
like, I don't know what you're
talking about, buddy.

00:45:20.250 --> 00:45:22.780
ERIC SCHMIDT: Yes, ma'am?

00:45:22.780 --> 00:45:24.890
AUDIENCE: I was just wondering
if you have anything left on

00:45:24.890 --> 00:45:27.100
your career wish list?

00:45:27.100 --> 00:45:28.740
STEPHEN COLBERT: Sure.

00:45:28.740 --> 00:45:29.860
I just don't know.

00:45:29.860 --> 00:45:33.270
I never know what's going
to happen even tomorrow.

00:45:33.270 --> 00:45:35.480
I just got to spend the week
with some of my favorite

00:45:35.480 --> 00:45:39.440
creative artists with "The
Hobbit." It was unbelievable.

00:45:39.440 --> 00:45:42.730
Weta Workshop made me
my own hobbit feet.

00:45:42.730 --> 00:45:47.140
Next week, I get to sing with
all these wonderful artists

00:45:47.140 --> 00:45:48.300
doing Christmas carols.

00:45:48.300 --> 00:45:49.510
I've done my own Christmas
special.

00:45:49.510 --> 00:45:52.990
I've had a rally on the mall.

00:45:52.990 --> 00:45:56.020
I've testified before
Congress.

00:45:56.020 --> 00:46:02.670
I may or may not appear
in "The Hobbit."

00:46:02.670 --> 00:46:04.390
The nice thing about my
show-- and whether or

00:46:04.390 --> 00:46:05.310
not I do show forever--

00:46:05.310 --> 00:46:06.080
I mean, everything ends.

00:46:06.080 --> 00:46:08.630
But whether or not I do the show
forever, the nice thing

00:46:08.630 --> 00:46:11.660
about my show is that as the
host and executive producer, I

00:46:11.660 --> 00:46:17.120
get to ask of myself anything
I want to try.

00:46:17.120 --> 00:46:20.190
But that also means, I have
to do everything I know.

00:46:20.190 --> 00:46:23.300
And so it's just this tremendous
sort of refreshing

00:46:23.300 --> 00:46:26.770
gift, as tiring as the show
is, because I am kind of

00:46:26.770 --> 00:46:28.200
decaying before your eyes.

00:46:31.170 --> 00:46:33.870
In the same the way, it's
also rejuvenating.

00:46:33.870 --> 00:46:37.480
Because the show is only
what I want it to be.

00:46:37.480 --> 00:46:41.080
I can always say no to myself
or ask myself something new.

00:46:41.080 --> 00:46:44.110
But beyond this, I just want
to work with people I like.

00:46:44.110 --> 00:46:45.320
I love the people I work with.

00:46:45.320 --> 00:46:46.490
I love what we do.

00:46:46.490 --> 00:46:47.900
And I just want to be able
to do it with joy.

00:46:47.900 --> 00:46:49.860
And the moment I can't do that,
I have got to stop and

00:46:49.860 --> 00:46:51.400
try to do something else.

00:46:51.400 --> 00:46:53.400
AUDIENCE: There are times when
you've taken your persona

00:46:53.400 --> 00:46:55.350
outside of the show itself,
like when you ran for

00:46:55.350 --> 00:46:56.750
president or started
your Super PAC.

00:46:56.750 --> 00:47:00.480
And I was curious, how did you
get the idea to do that?

00:47:00.480 --> 00:47:03.130
Or why did you decide to start
taking the character outside

00:47:03.130 --> 00:47:04.380
of the show itself?

00:47:06.920 --> 00:47:09.790
STEPHEN COLBERT: Well, he thinks
he belongs everywhere.

00:47:09.790 --> 00:47:10.500
You know what I mean?

00:47:10.500 --> 00:47:11.750
He thinks he belongs
everywhere.

00:47:11.750 --> 00:47:13.552
AUDIENCE: So did he make the
decision, or did you?

00:47:17.800 --> 00:47:19.020
STEPHEN COLBERT:
You know what?

00:47:19.020 --> 00:47:20.190
ERIC SCHMIDT: That sounds like
one of those Google--

00:47:20.190 --> 00:47:21.410
STEPHEN COLBERT: My ego is just
big enough that I'd like

00:47:21.410 --> 00:47:24.150
to think I'm in the
driver's seat.

00:47:24.150 --> 00:47:24.670
But I'm not entirely sure.

00:47:24.670 --> 00:47:25.610
ERIC SCHMIDT: That sounds
like one of those

00:47:25.610 --> 00:47:26.980
Google lawyer questions.

00:47:26.980 --> 00:47:28.355
Are you a Google lawyer?

00:47:28.355 --> 00:47:29.930
AUDIENCE: No, I'm an engineer.

00:47:29.930 --> 00:47:31.180
ERIC SCHMIDT: Ah, even worse.

00:47:33.380 --> 00:47:34.930
Very precise.

00:47:34.930 --> 00:47:38.470
STEPHEN COLBERT: I like putting
him in situations.

00:47:38.470 --> 00:47:41.740
Because he thinks he belongs
everywhere, anywhere he goes,

00:47:41.740 --> 00:47:45.670
as long as we can prepare
for the situation,

00:47:45.670 --> 00:47:46.900
I rarely take him.

00:47:46.900 --> 00:47:48.220
I do talk shows,
like right now.

00:47:48.220 --> 00:47:51.020
Or if I go on Dave, or I do
any news talk shows or

00:47:51.020 --> 00:47:54.240
anything like that, or even the
books tour, any place I

00:47:54.240 --> 00:47:55.990
would do it, I'm only myself.

00:47:55.990 --> 00:47:59.450
I could lapse into him or the
way he might behave at times.

00:47:59.450 --> 00:48:02.500
But out of context, he clangs
against the world.

00:48:02.500 --> 00:48:04.560
And I have to be prepared
for that clang.

00:48:04.560 --> 00:48:06.690
And so I'm very prepared for
the correspondents' dinner.

00:48:06.690 --> 00:48:08.150
We're very prepared for
the rally in the mall.

00:48:08.150 --> 00:48:09.290
I'm very prepared
to go to Iraq.

00:48:09.290 --> 00:48:12.520
I'm very prepared to testify
before Congress.

00:48:12.520 --> 00:48:17.040
I'm very prepared to give a
testimony any place, appear

00:48:17.040 --> 00:48:21.750
before the FEC, or give a speech
to supporters on the

00:48:21.750 --> 00:48:24.060
streets of Washington, DC.

00:48:24.060 --> 00:48:25.790
There's a lot of preparation
that goes into that.

00:48:25.790 --> 00:48:27.330
And I like it because
I like changing the

00:48:27.330 --> 00:48:29.230
context of a space.

00:48:29.230 --> 00:48:33.690
I like changing the context of
a supposedly not performance

00:48:33.690 --> 00:48:36.375
space into a performance
space and to see--

00:48:40.530 --> 00:48:42.380
well, here's what
I like to do.

00:48:42.380 --> 00:48:46.060
I like to think of the character
as a pebble that I

00:48:46.060 --> 00:48:49.825
can throw into the news and then
report on my own ripples.

00:48:54.970 --> 00:48:57.600
And I've said this before, but
Jon Stewart has characterized

00:48:57.600 --> 00:49:00.990
what he does as sitting at the
back of America's classroom

00:49:00.990 --> 00:49:03.560
and shooting spit balls.

00:49:03.560 --> 00:49:05.910
I am the spit ball.

00:49:05.910 --> 00:49:08.540
And I like to shoot myself into
it and see what it looks

00:49:08.540 --> 00:49:10.270
like when I'm in a news story.

00:49:10.270 --> 00:49:15.580
For instance, appointed Senator
of South Carolina.

00:49:15.580 --> 00:49:16.760
That's interesting.

00:49:16.760 --> 00:49:17.680
I didn't intend that.

00:49:17.680 --> 00:49:22.320
Usually the best ones, I didn't
actuate, I didn't push.

00:49:22.320 --> 00:49:23.750
They were invitations.

00:49:23.750 --> 00:49:25.840
I didn't say, I want to testify
before Congress.

00:49:25.840 --> 00:49:27.060
They asked me.

00:49:27.060 --> 00:49:30.430
And I said, you know this is
going to be a terrible idea?

00:49:30.430 --> 00:49:31.780
And they said, we want
you to come anyway.

00:49:31.780 --> 00:49:33.360
And I said, all right.

00:49:33.360 --> 00:49:35.820
In the same way, yesterday I
was just walking around,

00:49:35.820 --> 00:49:36.900
nothing happening.

00:49:36.900 --> 00:49:38.880
And suddenly, there was
a horse underneath me.

00:49:38.880 --> 00:49:41.370
And it was me being Senator
from South Carolina.

00:49:41.370 --> 00:49:42.690
I thought, how delightful.

00:49:42.690 --> 00:49:46.060
How delightful that we've
planned all these seeds of

00:49:46.060 --> 00:49:47.740
political activism
in my home state.

00:49:47.740 --> 00:49:50.780
And it is a reasonable,
ridiculous thing to surmise

00:49:50.780 --> 00:49:52.700
that I might get the job.

