accidental.

00:52:52.785 --> 00:52:55.140
For instance, Second City.

00:52:55.140 --> 00:52:56.310
I didn't think I was going
to be comedian.

00:52:56.310 --> 00:52:58.760
I had a secret desire as a high

00:52:58.760 --> 00:53:00.390
schooler to be a comedian.

00:53:00.390 --> 00:53:02.120
I didn't know what that meant.

00:53:02.120 --> 00:53:03.400
I just really liked
being funny.

00:53:03.400 --> 00:53:04.750
I'm from one of 11 kids.

00:53:04.750 --> 00:53:06.830
And we're a funny family.

00:53:06.830 --> 00:53:10.090
And being funny is important.

00:53:10.090 --> 00:53:12.640
The king of the room was
whoever was funniest.

00:53:12.640 --> 00:53:18.350
And I remember as a child,
seeing comedy helped.

00:53:18.350 --> 00:53:20.480
My family had a tragedy
when I was younger.

00:53:20.480 --> 00:53:22.430
My father and two of
my brothers died.

00:53:22.430 --> 00:53:22.950
ERIC SCHMIDT: Oh, I'm sorry.

00:53:22.950 --> 00:53:26.430
STEPHEN COLBERT: And I remember
my sister making

00:53:26.430 --> 00:53:30.910
another one of my sisters laugh
so hard in the car away

00:53:30.910 --> 00:53:32.980
from the cemetery.

00:53:32.980 --> 00:53:34.590
One of my sisters made the other
sisters laugh so hard

00:53:34.590 --> 00:53:37.910
that she fell on the floor of
the limo, one of those big

00:53:37.910 --> 00:53:39.590
floors, with the rumble seat
facing each other.

00:53:39.590 --> 00:53:41.550
And she fell on the
floor laughing.

00:53:41.550 --> 00:53:44.440
And I remember thinking,
I want to do that.

00:53:44.440 --> 00:53:46.450
I don't know whether it was
specifically in the context of

00:53:46.450 --> 00:53:49.560
dealing with tragedy, because
I was only 10.

00:53:49.560 --> 00:53:52.810
But I remember specifically
thinking, I want that.

00:53:52.810 --> 00:53:55.540
I'd love to have been able
to do that right now.

00:53:55.540 --> 00:54:00.450
And then I fell asleep every
night for years listening to

00:54:00.450 --> 00:54:05.940
